{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> πόκος</b>, ὁ, <br /> (πέκω) <b>wool</b> in its raw state, <b>fleece,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 12.451, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 574, “GDI” iv p.886 (Erythrae, 4th c.BC), “PCair.Zen.” 287, 774 (3rd c.BC), LXX.Judg.6.37; οἶν μελάγχιμον πόκῳ 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Electra” 513; πεκτεῖν.. προβάτων π. ἠρινόν 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 714; πέντε πόκως ἔλαβ᾽ ἐχθές 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 15.20 \">LXX+8th c.BC+</a>]; <b>lock</b> or <b>tuft of wool,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 675; ἐρίων π. 5th c.BC: Cratinus Comicus 372 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νεφέλαι πόκοις ἐρίων ὁμοῖαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “de Signis Tempestatum” 13. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> proverbial, εἰς ὄνου πόκας to an ass-<b>shearing,</b> i.e. to no-place, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 186 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὄνου πόκους or πόκας ζητεῖς you ask for 'pigeons'-milk', [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Zenobius Paroemiographus 5.38, etc.:—the _nominative_ of this phrase is given as πόκες by Scholia 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus [same place], as πόκαι by 10th c.AD: Suidas Legal icographus, 9th c.AD: Photius Legal icographus, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Ὄκνου πλοκάς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (ὄκνος 11) was probably read by 3rd-2nd c.BC: Aristarchus Grammaticus in 5th c.BC: Cratinus Comicus 348 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], and should perhaps be read in Ar.[same place]; οὐδεὶς πόκον εἰς γναφεῖον φέρει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Arcesilaus Comicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 8.624. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G8838","accentedUnicode":"πόκος","shortDef":"fleece","mediumDef":"fleece","stepGloss"